## 6. Design Patterns Used

### Supplier Pattern for Lazy Credential Loading

**Pattern:** Functional interface that provides values on-demand

**Benefits:**
- **Lazy Evaluation** - Credentials fetched only when needed
- **Refresh Capability** - Can re-fetch on each call
- **Error Isolation** - Failures at usage time, not startup
- **Testability** - Easy to mock

**Implementation:**
```java
@Service
public class CyberArkService {
    
    public Supplier<String> getCredentialSupplier(String secretId) {
        return () -> {
            // Executed only when get() is called
            Credential cred = cyberArkClient.retrieve(secretId);
            return cred.getPassword();
        };
    }
}

// Usage
@Component
public class DatabaseConfig {
    private Supplier<String> passwordSupplier;
    
    @PostConstruct
    public void init() {
        passwordSupplier = cyberArkService.getCredentialSupplier("db-password");
        // No network call yet!
    }
    
    public void connect() {
        String password = passwordSupplier.get();  // Fetched NOW
    }
}
```

### Adapter Pattern (Converting Credential to PropertySource)

**Pattern:** Converts one interface (Credential) to another (PropertySource) that clients expect

**Implementation:**
```java
// CyberArk returns Credential objects
public class Credential {
    private String username;
    private String password;
    // ...
}

// Spring expects PropertySource
public class MapPropertySource extends PropertySource<Map<String, Object>> {
    // ...
}

// Adapter: Convert Credential → PropertySource
@Component
public class CyberArkPropertyLoader {
    
    @PostConstruct
    public void loadSecrets() {
        // 1. Get Credentials from CyberArk (one format)
        List<Credential> credentials = cyberArkService.retrieveAll();
        
        // 2. Convert to Map (adapter step)
        Map<String, Object> properties = new HashMap<>();
        for (Credential cred : credentials) {
            properties.put(cred.getKey(), cred.getValue());
        }
        
        // 3. Wrap in PropertySource (adapter step)
        PropertySource<?> propertySource = new MapPropertySource("cyberark", properties);
        
        // 4. Spring can now use it (expected format)
        environment.getPropertySources().addFirst(propertySource);
    }
}
```

**Why It's an Adapter:**
- CyberArk provides credentials in one format
- Spring expects PropertySource format
- Adapter converts between the two formats
- Client code (@Value) doesn't need to know about the conversion

### Separation of Concerns (Service, Config, Loader Layers)

**Pattern:** Divide responsibilities into distinct layers

**Layer 1: Service Layer (CyberArkService)**
- **Responsibility:** Communicate with CyberArk API
- **Concerns:** Network calls, authentication, error handling
- **Does NOT know about:** Spring, PropertySources, @Value

```java
@Service
public class CyberArkService {
    public Credential retrieveSecret(String id) {
        // CyberArk API communication
        return cyberArkClient.get(id);
    }
}
```

**Layer 2: Configuration Layer (CyberArkConfig)**
- **Responsibility:** Define beans and Spring configuration
- **Concerns:** Bean creation, dependency setup
- **Does NOT know about:** Property loading, @Value resolution

```java
@Configuration
public class CyberArkConfig {
    @Bean
    public CyberArkClient cyberArkClient() {
        return new CyberArkClient();
    }
    
    @Bean
    public CyberArkService cyberArkService(CyberArkClient client) {
        return new CyberArkService(client);
    }
}
```

**Layer 3: Loader Layer (CyberArkPropertyLoader)**
- **Responsibility:** Bridge CyberArk and Spring PropertySources
- **Concerns:** PropertySource creation, Environment integration
- **Knows about:** Both CyberArkService and Spring Environment

```java
@Component
public class CyberArkPropertyLoader {
    @Autowired
    private CyberArkService service;  // Uses service layer
    
    @Autowired
    private ConfigurableEnvironment environment;  // Uses Spring layer
    
    @PostConstruct
    public void loadSecrets() {
        // Orchestrates: Service → PropertySource → Environment
        Credential cred = service.retrieveSecret("db.password");
        MapPropertySource source = new MapPropertySource("cyberark", map);
        environment.getPropertySources().addFirst(source);
    }
}
```

**Benefits:**
- **Testability** - Each layer can be tested independently
- **Maintainability** - Changes to CyberArk API only affect service layer
- **Reusability** - Service layer can be used without Spring
- **Clarity** - Each class has a single, clear responsibility

